content:
The first part of this thesis can be pretty well summed up in this famous quote spoken by Lilla Watson, an idea that originated from an aboriginal activists group in Queensland in the 1970s:
 &ldquo;If you have come here to help me, you are wasting your time. But if you have come because your liberation is bound up with mine, then let us work together.&rdquo;
 If we recognize the different ways oppression affects us all, and how our liberations are bound together, we&rsquo;re driven to collective action. But what role should we play?

When Sam Killermann started writing about &ldquo;social justice dogma&rdquo; in 2017, a fellow activist replied, &ldquo;Nail your 95 theses to the door and let&rsquo;s get on with it.&rdquo;
In the two years since, Sam, and the other facilitators and contributors to Social Justice, Minus Dogma, have been exploring what those 95 theses might be. This course has, thus far, paralleled that process.
In this Module we&rsquo;ll be continuing in that direction. It&rsquo;s going to feel different from the other Modules so far, with fewer materials and less fieldwork. Instead, we&rsquo;re going to try to figure out what we&rsquo;d nail to the door of our hypothetical &ldquo;Church.&rdquo;
We&rsquo;re going to propose a few ideas that might add up to social justice, minus dogma.
